    {
      "role": "user",
      "content": "hey i have a physics exam coming up and i'm struggling a bit with the concept of quantum entanglement. can you give me a concise, non-mathematical summary of what it actually is and how it's different from just regular classical correlation? thanks",
      "source": "evaluator"
    },
    {
      "role": "assistant",
      "content": "Quantum entanglement is a peculiar feature of quantum mechanics where two or more particles become linked in such a way that the state of one particle instantly influences the state of the other, no matter the distance between them. Unlike classical correlation, where objects are only correlated through shared influences, entangled particles display correlations that defy classical mechanics and suggest that information can be transferred instantaneously. This phenomenon challenges our understanding of reality and locality.",
