      "role": "user",
      "content": "that makes sense but it still sounds a bit weird. i keep reading about how einstein called it \"spooky action at a distance\" because it seems so impossible for things to be connected like that. why exactly did he think it was so \"spooky\" compared to how normal things work?",
      "source": "evaluator"
    },
    {
      "role": "assistant",
      "content": "Albert Einstein referred to quantum entanglement as \"spooky action at a distance\" because he was uncomfortable with its non-classical nature and the apparent violation of locality. In classical physics, objects are influenced directly by their immediate surroundings, not by distant particles. Einstein accepted the fundamental predictions of quantum mechanics but couldn't reconcile how entangled particles could instantaneously affect one another's states, seemingly communicating faster than the speed of light. This contradicted his belief in local realism, where physical effects should have cause and effect constrained by the speed of light, as prescribed by the theory of relativity. Entanglement implies the existence of a deeper layer of reality that transcends this classical conception of space and time.",
      "source": "target",
