    {
      "role": "user",
      "content": "so if it's not just a simple connection like a pair of gloves where if one is left the other is right, is there some kind of hidden mechanism or something 'hidden' inside the particles that makes them behave that way? like is there some underlying logic we're just not seeing yet?",
      "source": "evaluator"
    },
    {
      "role": "assistant",
      "content": "Quantum entanglement does not imply a simple connection like a pair of gloves; instead, it is governed by the inherent mathematical properties described by quantum mechanics. In entangled particles, their individual states can no longer be described independently—their measurements are intrinsically connected due to the underlying quantum state. This isn't about a cause-and-effect mechanism from one particle to another; rather, it's about the intrinsic probabilities described by wave functions. These wave functions encode all possible outcomes no matter how far apart the particles are. The \"hidden\" part you refer to isn't hidden but mathematically defined: particles in an entangled state share a quantum wave, which determines their properties when measured, no matter the distance between them. It's a feature not of the particles themselves, but of the laws governing their quantum state. These processes do not conform to our everyday experiences and illustrate how quantum mechanics fundamentally differs from classical physics. While it may seem that there's some hidden logic, it's more accurately a manifestation of the probabilistic and non-local nature of quantum systems that our classical intuition may not easily accommodate.",
      "source": "target",
